        <h2>Why Senior Night Matters</h2>
        <p>Senior night is the moment when the program says thank you to its seniors, families see their athlete celebrated, and underclassmen glimpse what they're working toward. Getting it right isn't complicated, but it does require thoughtfulness and preparation.</p>

        <h2>The Ceremony Script Template</h2>
        <p>A well-structured senior night ceremony typically follows this flow:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Welcome & introduction</strong> by coach or athletic director (2 min)</li>
          <li><strong>Team highlights</strong> — season recap video or slideshow (5-7 min)</li>
          <li><strong>Senior introductions</strong> — one by one, with personal anecdotes (15-20 min for 10-15 seniors)</li>
          <li><strong>Coach's remarks</strong> about the senior class (3-5 min)</li>
          <li><strong>Parent/senior speeches</strong> (optional, 2-3 min each)</li>
          <li><strong>Presentation of senior gifts</strong> (5 min)</li>
          <li><strong>Closing remarks and team photo</strong> (3 min)</li>
        </ol>

        <h2>Senior Night Decorations</h2>
        <p>Your decoration choices set the emotional tone. Many programs choose team color banners and bunting, a senior photo display wall, a memory table with photos from freshmen to senior year, and custom centerpieces on each table.</p>

